@model ScottNeidig.Web.Models.ServicePageModel
@*
    .NET application development page. BACKED: Scott has 25 years of .NET behind him, so this
    leads with existing-app work (maintain / fix / extend), which is his strongest, most
    defensible claim and the widest market. Fresh builds are one option, not the headline, so
    nobody reads him as fresh-builds-only.

    Copy is restrained placeholder for Scott to sharpen. Every claim is one he can stand behind.
    Do NOT name any organization (ASRS etc.) as a client: those are targets he hopes for, not
    work he's done. "Professional associations / membership platforms" as a KIND of client is
    fine; implying he's served one is not.
*@

<section class="section--lede">
    <div class="container">
        <p class="topper">.NET application development</p>
        <h1 class="header">Help with your existing .NET application</h1>
        <p class="text lede__text">
            Got a .NET site or application that needs looking after? I maintain, fix and extend
            existing systems, add the features you've been putting off, and build new ones when
            that's what's needed.
        </p>
        <a class="button button--lg" asp-controller="Contact" asp-action="Index">Schedule a consultation</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section--alt">
    <div class="container">
        <p class="topper">What I help with</p>
        <h2 class="title">Existing systems, not just new ones</h2>

        <ul class="features">
            <li class="feature">
                <h3 class="feature__title">Maintenance and fixes</h3>
                <p class="feature__text">
                    Keeping a working application working: bugs, breakages, and the things that
                    have been on the list too long.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li class="feature">
                <h3 class="feature__title">New features</h3>
                <p class="feature__text">
                    Adding to what you already run, without a rebuild, and without breaking what
                    already works.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li class="feature">
                <h3 class="feature__title">Integrations</h3>
                <p class="feature__text">
                    Connecting your application to the other systems your organization depends
                    on: payments, membership, events, third-party services.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li class="feature">
                <h3 class="feature__title">New builds</h3>
                <p class="feature__text">
                    When a new application is the right call, built on ASP.NET Core and made to
                    last.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</section>

<section>
    <div class="container">
        <p class="topper">Who it's for</p>
        <h2 class="title">Organizations running on .NET</h2>
        <p class="text">
            Businesses and professional organizations with a .NET application they rely on and
            need a steady hand for, whether that's a membership platform, an internal system, or
            a customer-facing site. Someone who can pick up an existing codebase and work in it,
            not only start from scratch.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

@*
    The backend/AI edge (Scott's positioning, 2026-07-17). This is his moat: web-only builders
    can't do the back end. Aimed at the larger-org tier, which is the buyer that has real
    problems and cares about AI (small-business owners don't). AI is a BACKED capability, not a
    claimed expertise: Jambalam ships ONE real AI feature, so the honest line is "built AI into a
    live product," never "AI specialist/expert." Keep it that way.
*@
<section class="section--alt">
    <div class="container">
        <p class="topper">The hard part</p>
        <h2 class="title">The back end, not just the front</h2>
        <p class="text">
            Plenty of people can put up a page. Fewer can build what sits behind it: the
            database, the business logic, the system that actually solves the problem. That's
            the work I do, and it's where a real application pulls ahead of a template.
        </p>
        <p class="text">
            That includes AI where it earns its place. I've built AI into a live product,
            Jambalam, using Azure AI to power a working feature people use, not a demo. If your
            organization is weighing what AI could do in your systems, that's a conversation I
            can have from experience.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section--alt">
    <div class="container">
        <p class="topper">Why me</p>
        <h2 class="title">25 years of .NET, working directly with you</h2>
        <p class="text">
            I've spent my career building and maintaining .NET applications, a lot of it at
            agencies where this work bills at a premium. Working with me directly, you get that
            experience without the agency layer in between, and you talk to the person doing the
            work.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

@* Proof comes from the category assigned to this page in the admin. *@
<partial name="_RelatedProjects" model="Model" />

<partial name="_CallToAction" model="@("Need work on your .NET application?")" />
